BASIC ANALYSIS

Variables

I would like to pick a couple of explanatory variables of interest: GDP per capita & happiness score in different regions.

world_happiness <- WHR %>%
  select(Economy_GDP_per_Capita, Happiness.Score, Region)

Get some summary numbers

Using summary() function to get some summary information here.

world_happiness %>% summary(
  mean_economy = mean(Economy_GDP_per_Capita, na.rm=TRUE),
  sd_economy = sd(Economy_GDP_per_Capita, na.rm = TRUE)
)

Make a Box graph

ggplot(world_happiness, aes(x=Economy_GDP_per_Capita,y=Happiness.Score))+
  geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Continuous x aesthetic -- did you forget aes(group=...)?

I found

The the average GDP per capita value is 0.9102 and maximum is 1.6904; the average happiness score is 5.232 and the minimum is 2.839. Furthermore, in 2015, the happiness score in most countries haven’t reached to the average level.

Make a histogram of the Economy

ggplot(world_happiness, aes(x=Economy_GDP_per_Capita)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

And happiness score

ggplot(world_happiness, aes(x=Happiness.Score))+
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

And region

ggplot(world_happiness, aes(x=Region))+
  geom_histogram(stat="count")
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: binwidth, bins, pad

I found

Sub-Saharan Africa has the largest number of countries, and most countries’ happiness score is less than 6 and most countries GDP is less than 1.0 in the world.

MULTIVARIATE EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS

Plot interaction model

ggplot(world_happiness, 
       aes(x = Economy_GDP_per_Capita, y = Happiness.Score, col = Region)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(y = "Happiness.Score", 
       x = "Economy_GDP_per_Capita", 
       title = "Happiness")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

I found

The overall slope demonstrates that the higher GDP possibly cause to the higher happiness score. Albeit Western Europe countries haven’t the highest GDP, the people there are the happiest in the world.

The parallel slopes model

ggplot(world_happiness, 
       aes(x = Economy_GDP_per_Capita, y = Happiness.Score, col = Region)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_parallel_slopes(se = FALSE) +
  labs(y = "Happiness.Score", 
       x = "Economy_GDP_per_Capita", 
       title = "Happiness & Economy")

I found

With the same slope, the western Europe line is in the top of the graph, but it is not in the rightmost. Therefore the conclusion came out which it’s true that people will happier if they have more money but there are other important factors contributing to people’s happiness.

Analyze in the different angles in terms of regions

Get some summary numbers using group by function

world_happiness <- world_happiness %>% 
  group_by(Region) %>% 
  summarize(mean_score = mean(Happiness.Score, na.rm = TRUE), 
            sd_score = sd(Happiness.Score, na.rm = TRUE))

Visualize the summary date though a Boxplot with individual data points

world_happiness <- WHR
ggplot(world_happiness, 
       aes(x = Economy_GDP_per_Capita, y = Happiness.Score, col = Region)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, alpha=0.6) +
  geom_jitter(color='black', size=0.4, alpha=0.9) +
  ggtitle("happiness score in different region") +
  xlab("")

(Reference https://www.r-graph-gallery.com/89-box-and-scatter-plot-with-ggplot2.html)

I found

Through the boxplot, I can tell that most the countries in Western Europe, Eastern Asia, Southeastern Asia have beyond the average happiness score in respective regions.

Fit a regression model with the interaction

happiness_model <- lm( Happiness.Score~ Economy_GDP_per_Capita, 
                     data = world_happiness)

View the model coefficients with get_regression_table()

get_regression_table(happiness_model)
## # A tibble: 2 × 7
##   term                   estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
##   <chr>                     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 intercept                  3.50     0.133      26.3       0     3.24     3.76
## 2 Economy_GDP_per_Capita     2.22     0.142      15.6       0     1.94     2.50

This looks really simple regression which is “happiness score ~ intercept + Economy_GDP_per_Capita” that is 3.50 + 2.22 * Economy_GDP_per_Capita

Visualize the model

ggplot(happiness_model, aes(x = Economy_GDP_per_Capita, y = Happiness.Score)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Economy", y = "Happiness Score",
       title = "Relationship between economy and happiness scores") +  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

CONCLUSION

In a nutshell, the relationship between Economy and Human Happiness is corresponding to our common sense which is positive relevance.
